There have been instances where teachers have given the answers of the tests to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the contrary send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a particular day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are lousy lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential competence that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to write: "I had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have carried out an in-depth research of such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths on the lie have been demystified.
The liars look into your eyes.
They don't swallow, pray or don't always bother.
Do not conclude that liars are hard to detect and hard to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation and time of answer.
I have spent many years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are skilled at reading others, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect the feelings of someone - that married people less often lie to their partners than unwed people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you're perceived as a disbeliever, the others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "setting the benchmark data."
This helps to provide a point of reference to measure subsequent changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone usually removes his feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him kicking his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for hints of verbal and nonverbal deceptive behaviour.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Lying people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their history, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change their posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated breath of relief, a change of posture when all difficult questions are passed.
Questionors often falsely indicate that the interview is just finished to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, watch out for your subject vocabulary.
The famous Scott Peterson broke up using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceitful individuals can also use a distant language: "I have not had sexual relations with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" in his answer to a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember good... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
