In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
"I also consider that if it is done, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he recalled that planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, who has the constitutional mandate of the government.
Substituting analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this results in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To adjourn the change, he said, would adjourn the benefits of digitisation which implies a decision of public interest which not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of a whole system to establish, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the Faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had the highly specialized technical organs.
