In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Aid Services, ensured that the moment of impact, the state helicopter Presidential Major was operating at the speed of cruising and this happened on a rolling ground.
"This information supports the assumption that normal operation will crumble at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, TBS licensee Pérez Jácome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of the visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned appropriate conditions for take-off, and as and as the aircraft moved towards the border area between DF and the state of Mexico, there were layers of low-level nebulosity.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the nebulosity conditions the crew sought a lower and more visible area of height towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remaining parts of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available to date allows us to assume that the impact has taken place on a straight and lateral path.
The aircraft residue dispersal model allows us to assume that the helicopter has struck against the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No traces of fire or explosion were detected:
There is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple ground contacts.
During the field work, aircraft parts were found at a height of 9 thousand 200 feet above the average sea level, with a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
Photographs show the sequence in which he was possibly disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a larger area than the surrounding area around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the assumption that the impact took place in structural integrity conditions.
MSS ad protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Assurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of the obesity of children and adolescents' that will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialities Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and third-cycle students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) from the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate in the population with or without the right to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valle de México, where the evidence is given to minors every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sport Unit (State of Mexico West) and that as of 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sport Unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of Federal District) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for children and young Mexicans to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on World Diabetes Day, he noted that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, glucose levels determination, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetics (one seeks to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity in boys and 47 per cent in girls; in overweight, there was also a dramatic increase in overweight, the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent indo-American inheritance, 30 per cent in Europe and 5 per cent in Africa, and this is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translate into the inability to burn the excess of energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full evaluation of children, which allows them to detect if they present a degree of overweight or obesity.
It even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors write it back to parents, to whom each explains the measures and changes in the lifestyle they have to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use of means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is high calorie intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pulp to corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would prevent the cassia
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs were resolved, there would be no need to repair about 200 thousand cassia each rainy season in the Métropolitaine Zone of Valle de México, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemie (FQ) of UNAM, which ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cassses could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on the cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory responsible for it develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and consequently, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the paving its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and 50 degrees C it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in most of them were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, pointed out, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through with efforts, it allows the forces to propagate very well into the pavement.
If the asphalt was modified, the asphalt would propagate better, as the chemical engineer did.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the deck that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made of is to be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to do so, which blows all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first one that breaks is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Searcher System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the deck must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent training of cassation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cases easily and without having to use high temperatures.
