Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says an expert committee
Canadians live in the denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of a major report of the Royal Society of Canada, with six experts involved in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in such a way as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
If Canada has ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, they report to us experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire for most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that they do not want to change anything to the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, which have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-compliant or non-consent persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, said yesterday, there would be more cases of these spillovers precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"The assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie says.
Euthanasy Canadians
Let us recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow people in the end of their lives to ease their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the life of the elderly or disabled is less valuable.
