The North Stream, the new Russian gas port in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, went into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with bursts.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on Tuesday, on the Baltic shores, between orchestra and fine buffets, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Filon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the Land of Mecklembourg-Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has air of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will enable gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to the West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security from its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe of energy, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Filon by opening this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economical the major gas contracts are.
This explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it against ships' anchors.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
In order to build it, mines from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed by caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply the measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts all its length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off Sweden, but project managers gave up on it while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state society permanently settle off their shores.
"In the event of damage, we stop passing the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline is thus leaked into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to escape every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, trained by a ship, for external observation, and by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
Of the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide by one meter diameter, and is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to run 50 years without having to suffer the least repair.
Gas circulation is simply driven by pressure.
It is 200 bar at the beginning, and 100 bar at the arrival.
Five companies joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, holding 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for twenty renewable years, all of the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their fees, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters tall, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
